Anonymous Thu 01 Feb 2024 21:50:31 No.63005952 Report
Quoted By: >>63005993
>>63005652
NTA but I drop a lot of stories because they aren't really interested in a theme or saying anything interesting. They don't ask big moral questions. There's no "point" to the story besides characters dicking around ala slice of life.

This doesn't mean the story needs to be a political commentary or a space opera. It just means there needs to be claims like "Physical touch isn't the only way to express love." The questions are asked via conflict in the narrative and are answered by resolution.

For example: Waifur feels ignored by Anon because he doesn't take her on dates anymore. Shes distant, Anon does know why. Waifur rejects anon's initiation for sex in an angry burst. Anon is blindsided. Waifur has to explain how she feels after keeping it hidden. Anon has to choose to continue his way or change. By changing, and taking her on a date, he understands that the waifur needs different types of love, and asserts the claim.
